narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned some cool applications of integrals. For example, I learned that a shape with an infinite area can have a finite volume.
I learned how to problem solve and gained a solid foundation in integral calculus.
I learned more basic concepts of calculus and how to use them in application problems.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: I think that choosing of teachers can be better. Also, the reverse class room setting made it less ideal to learn but I think that was because of my professor because when I started attending Kyles review sessions I was able to digest all the information.
There is a large gap in the teaching abilities of the professors. The tests are fair and the videos every night help to learn the material.

The class covered a lot of information. However, that was part of the problem. It seemed to cover too much information. It was hard to keep up with all of the work and information as the class continued on. It would have been slightly more beneficial to learn less information and go deeper into the topics we did cover.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: I would recommend this course to anyone who enjoys math or needs it for a major, but not anyone else.

I would recommend this class to another student if it is required by their major. If not, I feel it would be way more interesting to take a different QR class and gain credit in a class that is actually more interesting to them than a general calculus class. It's not the most stimulating class.
